\begin_layout Section
Introduction
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
In this lab,
 we familiarized ourselves with using communication protocols (SPI and I2C,
 respectively) to communicate to peripheral devices with our CC3200 Microntroller Unit (MCU).
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
We used the SPI protocol to interact with an Adafruit SSD1351 OLED Digital Display (OLED),
 and perform drawing operations on it's screen.
 Using the general-purpose pins provided by the MCU,
 we can bind the signals defined by the SPI protocol and initiate communication via the SPI software development kit API.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
Then,
 we introduce I2C to extract acceleration data in 3 dimensions,
 from three registers defined by the MCU's on-board BMA222 Accelerometer.
 We focus on the x and y dimensions,
 determining the tilt & angle of the MCU in 8-bit 2's complement form,
 from two respective registers.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
Combining our ability to communicate with the OLED and determine accelerometer information,
 we can tilt the accelerometer and get a velocity response from drawn pixels on the OLED.
 Mainly,
 we move a circle around the OLED display.
 More information on how this works will be included in subsequent sections.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
In completing this lab,
 we effectively learn how to work with MCU-supported communication protocols,
 and get it to do exciting things with peripheral devices,
 as well as utilize on-board MCU components to introduce additional functionality to these peripheral device programs that we otherwise wouldn't have.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Section
Background
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Modules,
 hardware,
 and software tools used are as follows.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
Modules
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate

\family typewriter
spi_demo:
 
\family default
Texas Instruments CCS project that demonstrates how to use SPI signals for simple UART communication.
 This module is co-opted and used for all parts of the lab when sending data to the OLED.
 Note this also includes usage for the MCU as both a master & slave:
 we leave just the code for master,
 since that is all that the MCU will be doing.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate

\family typewriter
i2c_demo:
 
\family default
Texas Instruments CCS project that demonstrates how to use I2C signals for simple reading operations with the BMA222 accelerometer.
 Namely,
 using the UART terminal to print out the changing accelerometer axis values (x,
 y,
 and z) when the MCU is rotated in physical space.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate

\family typewriter
Adafruit SSD1351 Open Source Graphics Library:
 
\family default
Abridged from the Adafruit graphics library,
 provides an API to write commands (and their subsequent data) to the OLED,
 as well as turn it on.
 Includes various functions to draw complex shapes on the digital display.
 This library is used extensively in this lab & modified.
 More information on the modifications will be detailed.
\end_layout

