\begin_layout Standard
For lines 1-11,
 we have defined some simple macros to make the two functions more readable.
 In short:
 
\family typewriter
DC_COMMAND()
\family default
 sets the DC pin to low,
 
\family typewriter
DC_DATA()
\family default
 sets the DC pin to high,
 
\family typewriter
CS_ENABLE()
\family default
 enables our chip select,
 and 
\family typewriter
CS_DISABLE()
\family default
 disables our chip select.
 With this in mind,
 
\family typewriter
writeCommand()
\family default
:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
Sets the DC to low (for Command type to the MOSI line)
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
Enables CS to low (indicating data is being transmitted)
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
Sends the 
\family typewriter
char c
\family default
 via SPI across the MOSI line
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
Disables CS to high (indicating data is no longer being transmitted).
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard

\family typewriter
writeData()
\family default
 is similar:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
Sets the DC to high (for Data type to the MOSI line)
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
Enables CS to low
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
Sends the 
\family typewriter
char c
\family default
 via SPI across the MOSI line
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
Disables CS to high
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
This specific protocol respects SPI and write commands and data to the OLED.
 This is used extensively for preparing to turn on the OLED and draw pixels on it's display.
 Fortunately the API takes care of the rest of the implementation details,
 and we need not concern ourself with the internals for this report.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
We can now focus on implementing the OLED output.
 After it is initialized,
 we use the following logic to complete the checkoff:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
First,
