\begin_layout Standard
So what's happening here?
 The device address is 
\family typewriter
0x18
\family default
,
 our original address,
 shifted to the left 1 bit.
 Why?
 It is actually 7-bit representation due to it actually being signed,
 so on the line,
 an extra 8th bit is added at the end.
 This is a 
\family typewriter
0
\family default
 if it is a write,
 and a 
\family typewriter
1
\family default
 if it is a read.
 The register pointer is where we are reading from,
 which corresponds to the x and y axis register.
 Finally,
 the data byte is what was actually read.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
If we piece this together and read the binary from left to right across the SDA,
 we can see it is accurate.
 The data bytes themselves,
 when converted to decimal,
 are -63 for X and 40 for Y.
 The sign indicates the angle on a given plane,
 and the value the magnitude.
 X is likely side-to-side,
 and Y forward-and-backward (when looking at the MCU from a top-down perspective,
 longways).
 This is pretty helpful for our next checkoff!
\end_layout

