\begin_layout Enumerate
To keep the ball moving,
 we enclose the main logic in a while loop.
 But on line 15,
 we start the position of the ball in the very center of the screen.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
Upon entering the loop,
 we write to the I2C registers asociaed with our X and Y value,
 then we read from it.
 This gives us the new tilt values in 2D space (we are ignoring the Z axis since the OLED is a flat screen).
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
With this value,
 we update the position,
 the new value is the current value plus the raw value extracted from the I2C registers;
 we multiply the raw value with a float constant to carefully control the speed of movement (smaller scalar value means less change!),
 on Lines 27 and 28.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
These new values are then compared against the width and height of the screen,
 on Lines 31-34.
 This ensures the ball is not allowed to go 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

off
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 the screen (more accurately,
 experience undefined behavior in the ball drawing function).
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
Lastly,
 we check if the ball needs to move on Line 37.
 If the new x or y differs from the previous x or y,
 we start by filling the pixels with white (where the ball used to be).
 We update the coordinates,
 then we render a new ball at these coordinates.
 The illuson of movement is complete!
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
Last,
 we call a delay command to have slightly less jitter;
 we don't want the input to be too responsive between iterations.
\end_layout

